  "prompt": "What is the W boson?",
  "response": "The W boson is an elementary particle that plays a crucial role in the weak force, one of the four fundamental forces of nature. The W bosons are responsible for mediating the weak nuclear force, which is responsible for processes such as beta decay in atomic nuclei. There are two types of W bosons: \\( W^+ \\) (positively charged) and \\( W^- \\) (negatively charged).\n\nHere are some key characteristics of the W boson:\n\n1. **Mass**: The W boson is quite massive compared to many other elementary particles, with a mass of about 80.379 GeV/c\u00b2.\n2. **Spin**: It has a spin of 1, making it a vector boson.\n3. **Charge**: The \\( W^+ \\) boson has a positive electric charge, while the \\( W^- \\) boson has a negative electric charge.\n4. **Interactions**: W bosons interact with all fermions, including quarks and leptons, which are the building blocks of matter.\n5. **Decay**: As they are unstable, W bosons can decay into other particles. Common decay products include quark-antiquark pairs or lepton-neutrino pairs.\n\nThe discovery of the W boson in 1983 at CERN provided significant confirmation of the electroweak unification, which combines the electromagnetic and weak forces into a single theoretical framework. This discovery was pivotal in the development of the Standard Model of particle physics.",
